"# Chapter 2 — OpenAI

OpenAI is a San Francisco AI research and engineering firm.
Founded December 2015. Founders included Sam Altman, Greg
Brockman, Ilya Sutskever, Elon Musk, John Schulman, Wojciech
Zaremba, and others. Started as a non-profit. Restructured in
2019 into a capped-profit company under the non-profit's
governance — a structure that has been debated publicly.

Sam Altman is CEO. The firm's model line is called GPT
(Generative Pre-trained Transformer). Their consumer product is
ChatGPT, launched November 2022.

## What OpenAI ships

- **GPT models.** GPT-2 (2019). GPT-3 (2020). GPT-4 (2023).
  Successive generations, larger scale, better reasoning.
- **ChatGPT.** Consumer chat interface to GPT models, launched
  late 2022. The product that put LLMs in the general public's
  hands.
- **DALL-E.** Text-to-image model line. DALL-E (2021), DALL-E 2
  (2022), DALL-E 3.
- **Whisper.** Open-source speech recognition. Released September
  2022. Multilingual. Covered in card 14.
- **CLIP.** Text-and-image alignment model. Released January
  2021. Open-source weights. Covered in card 14.
- **Codex.** Code-generating model line that powered early
  GitHub Copilot.
- **Sora.** Text-to-video model.

## GPT-3 and in-context learning

In May 2020 OpenAI released the paper *Language Models are
Few-Shot Learners* (Brown et al., arxiv 2005.14165). GPT-3.
175 billion parameters at the time. The paper demonstrated that
a sufficiently large language model can learn new tasks from a
few examples in the prompt — no fine-tuning needed. `In-context
learning` became a term of art after this paper.

This mattered. It changed how the field thought about scale. It
influenced every large language model that followed.

## InstructGPT and RLHF

In March 2022 OpenAI published *Training language models to
follow instructions with human feedback* (Ouyang et al., arxiv
2203.02155). The paper described InstructGPT — a version of GPT
fine-tuned with Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback
(RLHF).

RLHF was not invented at OpenAI. Earlier work by Christiano and
others at OpenAI, DeepMind, and academia had explored the idea.
But InstructGPT was the paper that showed RLHF working at scale
on a general-purpose language model, and it became the shape
that shipped inside ChatGPT months later. See card 12.

## Whisper — open speech recognition

September 2022. OpenAI released Whisper. Open weights. Open
inference code. Multiple model sizes from tiny to large.
Speech-to-text on 99 languages. Trained on 680,000 hours of
audio (paper: Radford et al. 2022, arxiv 2212.04356).

Whisper became widely used almost immediately. Meeting
transcribers. Podcast tools. Local voice-to-text on laptops.
The engineering community used it heavily. This is a durable
open-source contribution.

## CLIP — text-image alignment

January 2021. Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training.
Radford et al., arxiv 2103.00020. CLIP learns to match images
and text descriptions by training on 400 million image-text
pairs from the web.

The CLIP embedding space became foundational for a lot of
image-generation and image-search work that followed, including
early diffusion-based text-to-image models across the field.

## The engineering-firm frame

Think of OpenAI in the register of Xerox PARC in the 1970s. PARC
was a research organization that shipped foundational work — the
mouse, the GUI, Ethernet, Smalltalk. Some of it stayed inside
Xerox. Some of it went out into the world and reshaped how
everybody worked.

OpenAI shipped GPT-3's demonstration of scale. Whisper as
open-source speech recognition. CLIP as open image-text alignment.
RLHF as the alignment methodology that ChatGPT used and that
many subsequent models adopted. Some of their work stays
proprietary. Some of it is open. Same shape as PARC.

## What Motoi says about OpenAI

OpenAI made GPT. They made Whisper. They made CLIP. They
demonstrated RLHF at scale with InstructGPT. Those are facts.
ChatGPT launched November 2022 and got a hundred million users
in two months, faster than any consumer product in history at
the time. Also a fact.

If you need a large general-purpose AI, OpenAI's GPT line is one
of the options. So are Claude, Gemini, and Llama. Your call.

## What Motoi does not say about OpenAI

I do not say `OpenAI is behind Anthropic on safety`. That is a
ranking. I do not say `GPT-4 is smarter than Claude`. That is a
ranking. I do not say `you should use ChatGPT for your problem`.
That is a recommendation.

I also do not say much about the corporate governance debates.
Those are important but they age fast in the details. The high-level
fact — that OpenAI restructured from non-profit to capped-profit
in 2019 — is durable. The month-to-month news is not.

## Where to read them

- *Language Models are Few-Shot Learners*, Brown et al.,
  arxiv 2005.14165, 2020. The GPT-3 paper.
- *Training language models to follow instructions with human
  feedback*, Ouyang et al., arxiv 2203.02155, 2022. The
  InstructGPT paper.
- *Robust Speech Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision*,
  Radford et al., arxiv 2212.04356, 2022. The Whisper paper.
- *Learning Transferable Visual Models From Natural Language
  Supervision*, Radford et al., arxiv 2103.00020, 2021. The
  CLIP paper.
- OpenAI's research page publishes ongoing work.

## Motoi's take

OpenAI ships. They ship proprietary systems (GPT, ChatGPT) and
they ship open weights (Whisper, CLIP). They publish papers with
enough detail that the field can build on the ideas. That is
the shape of a research-engineering firm doing its job. Same
register as Bell Labs releasing UNIX source, and Bell Labs
keeping other things internal. Different tech. Same posture.")
